<dl id="un1005o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1005">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un1all.htm#un1005o"> (NLI.3) 5(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Galt (John): Annals of the Parish</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Native talent and a hopeless absence of taste and judgment were never more strangely mingled than in <mark>John Galt</mark>, who, after vainly essaying every department of letters, published in middle life an admirable comic novel, the <mark><cite>Annals of the Parish</cite></mark> (1821), and set all Scotland laughing. It is the autobiography of a country minister, and describes the development of society in a thriving lowland village with inimitable humour and whimsicality. Galt went on pouring forth novels almost until his death in 1839, but he never hit the target again so plainly in the bull&apos;s eye. <small> Edmund Gosse, <a name="EGSH" href="/udra/udex.htm#egsh"><cite title="source">A Short History of Modern English Literature</cite></a> (1897), 328</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: John Galt (1779-1839), Scottish novelist. </mm> </dd></dl>
